SECTION 7: SAPIENT-DERIVED INGREDIENTS

GENERAL RULING
The Society's position (per the Doctrine of Essences): Vampire Dust is acceptable.
Giant's Toe is contested. Human Heart is across the ethical line for most practitioners.

For GM purposes: any player using Human Heart or equivalent sapient-derived materials
should be aware that:

1. ANIMA compounds from sapient sources are stronger.
   When a sapient ANIMA ingredient is used, treat the ANIMA Essence as one quality tier
   higher for purposes of the Potency result (Standard becomes Potent, Potent becomes
   Exceptional). The spiritual concentration is simply greater.

2. Social consequences are real.
   Using, carrying, or being known to have used sapient-derived materials in a brewing
   context should trigger the same social stigma as Black Soul Gem use (Gear Doc):
   lawful or good-aligned NPCs may react with suspicion, report the characters,
   or in extreme cases attack.

3. ANIMA compounds from sapient sources interact unpredictably with active magic.
   If the target of a sapient-ANIMA compound has any active spell effect (enchantment,
   ongoing spell, Bound Weapon, etc.), the GM may call for an additional Guile roll
   from the alchemist. Failure means the ANIMA interacts with the existing magic in an
   unexpected way — the GM determines what that means. This is never lethal by default,
   but it is always interesting.

VAMPIRE DUST NOTE
Vampire Dust is the one sapient-derived ingredient that is ethically cleared.
Its ANIMA concentration is high (vampires' inner life is a significant part of their
nature) but it is not subject to the social stigma rules above. Serafine approves of
its use and says so in the Doctrine.


